******
[1] Michigan (Ionia County)
Date: Fri 21 Oct 2022
Source: Equus [edited]
https://equusmagazine.com/news/eq-edcc-health-watch/michigan-thoroughbred-recovering-from-strangles/


On 19 Oct 2022, the Michigan Department of Agriculture and Rural Development confirmed an unvaccinated 3-year-old Thoroughbred gelding in Ionia County is recovering from strangles. He began showing signs of nasal discharge on 2 Oct 2022. This is the 2nd confirmed case of strangles on the premises, with the original case occurring in August [2022].

Strangles in horses is an infection caused by _Streptococcus equi_ subspecies _equi _and spread through direct contact with other equids or contaminated surfaces. Horses which aren't showing clinical signs can harbor and spread the bacteria. Recovered horses remain contagious for at least 6 weeks, with the potential to cause outbreaks long-term.

Infected horses can exhibit a variety of clinical signs:

- Fever
- Swollen and/or abscessed lymph nodes
- Nasal discharge
- Coughing or wheezing
- Muscle swelling
- Difficulty swallowing

Veterinarians diagnose horses using polymerase chain reaction (PCR) testing with either a nasal swab, wash or an abscess sample. They treat most cases based on clinical signs, implementing antibiotics for severe cases. Overuse of antibiotics can prevent an infected horse from developing immunity. Most horses make a full recovery in 3 to 4 weeks.

A vaccine is available but not always effective. Biosecurity measures of quarantining new horses at a facility and maintaining high standards of hygiene and disinfecting surfaces can help lower the risk of outbreak or contain one when it occurs.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED Rapporteur Mahmoud Orabi

******
[2] Michigan (Lake County)
Date: Wed 28 Sep 2022
Source: Equus [abridged, edited]
https://equusmagazine.com/news/eq-edcc-health-watch/michigan-quarter-horse-positive-for-strangles/


On 23 Sep 2022, the Michigan Department of Agriculture and Rural Development confirmed a Quarter Horse cross yearling filly in Lake County positive for strangles. She presented with nasal discharge and coughing starting on 1 Sep 2022, and is recovering. Within the previous month [August 2022], a new horse had been purchased and added to the herd. Two other horses on the property have been exposed and are suspected positive.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED Rapporteur Mahmoud Orabi

